Introduction¶

As customer segmentation is an increasingly popular technique used by companies of all sizes to gain a better understanding of their customers and to tailor their products, services, and marketing efforts to meet the specific needs and preferences of different customer segments. This opportunity involves dividing a company's customer base into distinct groups based on common characteristics such as demographics, psychographics, and behavioral patterns.

In this project, I will implement the K-Means Clustering algorithm, which is one of the partition-based clustering algorithms commonly used today, to segment our existing customers into unique clusters based on their demographic and behavioral characterictics and will determine the different customer profiles that the firm have to what kind of responses these groups have provided to recent campaigns.

This dataset includes 4 main stream:

  • Demographic infromations about Customers includes such as id, birth year of the customer, their income level, the number of kids or teenagers in the household etc.

  • Behavioral informations that indicates customer buying habit regarding on different product categories including MntWines, MntFruits, MntMeatProducts, MntFishProducts etc.

  • Place information that indicates where customer bought the related products including:

    • number of purchases on website(NumWebPurchases)
    • number of purchases from the stores catalog (NumCatalogPurchases)

  • Informations about the recent campaings including:

    • amount of spending with promotions (NumDealsPurchases)
    • whether the customer accepted the campaings or not (AcceptCmp1, AcceptCmp2, AcceptCmp3 etc.)

Feature Engineering¶

  1. Year_Birth column just shows the year of birth. This situation can make the analysis hard to comprehend. Therefore, I decided to convert the column into Age column that shows the corresponding age of the customer.
In [ ]:
#Creating Age column
current_year = datetime.datetime.now().year
df['Age'] = current_year - df['Year_Birth']
  1. By summing up the procuts columns to get a total spending value for each customer. It might be a good indicator for the rest of the analysis
In [ ]:
#Creating total amount of spending for the products
cols = ["MntWines","MntFruits","MntMeatProducts","MntFishProducts","MntSweetProducts","MntGoldProds"]
df['TotalSpent'] = df[cols].sum(axis=1)
  1. Martial_Status columns unneccasirly classified when thinking about the purpose of the pipeline. Therefore, I simplified the various types of martial statues into two categories : "Partner" and "Alone".
In [ ]:
#Simplify Martiul Status
conditions = ["Married", "Together"]
values = "Partner"
df["Living_With"] = df["Marital_Status"].map(lambda x: values if x in conditions else "Alone")
  1. Again I simplified the number of children that the household had. Because the details is not needed in this project.
In [ ]:
#Total number of kids in the household
df["Children"] = df[["Kidhome", "Teenhome"]].sum(axis=1)
  1. I created this column to understand whether the customer is parent or not.
In [ ]:
#Are the customers parent or not 
df["Parenthood"] = (df["Children"] > 0).astype(int)
  1. Again, there is so much redundancy in the education column, simplified to basic educational levels.

There is newly 3 categories : Undergraduate, Graduate and Postgraduate

In [ ]:
#Segmenting column into three columns
education_map = {"Basic": "Undergraduate", 
                 "2n Cycle": "Undergraduate", 
                 "Graduation": "Graduate", 
                 "Master": "Postgraduate", 
                 "PhD": "Postgraduate"}
df["Education"] = df["Education"].map(education_map)

renaming some columns and removing unwanted columns

In [ ]:
#Renaming the confusing names and dropping the excessive features
df=df.rename(columns={"MntWines": "Wines","MntFruits":"Fruits","MntMeatProducts":"Meat","MntFishProducts":"Fish","MntSweetProducts":"Sweets","MntGoldProds":"Gold"})
to_drop = ["Marital_Status", "Dt_Customer", "Z_CostContact", "Z_Revenue", "Year_Birth", "ID"]
df = df.drop(to_drop, axis=1)

Data Preprocessing¶

In this section I will flow 4 main points in preprocessing stage:

  • Removing outliers

  • Encoding classification columns

  • droppping some features with the support of correlation matrix

  • Standardizing data for Principal Component Analysis

  • Implementing Dimensionality Reduction with PCA

1. Removing outliers¶

  • Firstly I decided to remove the outliers, because Kmeans Clustering techniques are very sensitive to outliers.

  • Therefore, it is important to visualize columns and check their datapoints in scatter plot to see if there is any anomaly in dataset.

  • After examining each features in scatterplot by comparing with other features.

It founded that the "Age" column and "Income" column has outliers that can effect the clustering algoritm.

In [ ]:
g1 = sns.pairplot(df[['Age','Income']])
g1.fig.set_size_inches(10, 8)
g1.fig.suptitle('Before outlier removal', y=1.02)
plt.show()

# Rules for outliers
df = df[(df["Age"]<100)]
df = df[(df["Income"]<120000)]
print("The total number of data-points after removing the outliers are:", len(df))

g2 = sns.pairplot(df[['Age','Income']])
g2.fig.set_size_inches(10, 8)
g2.fig.suptitle('After outlier removal', y=1.02)

The total number of data-points after removing the outliers are: 2020

2. Encoding¶

  • Encoding the dataset is necessary because Kmeans Clustering is only assumes the numerical values.

  • Therefore, I need to convert the categorical features to numerical vales.

  • While doing that I realized that the LabelEncoder() assigns a unique integer label to each category in the feature,
    starting with 0 for the first category and increasing by 1 for each subsequent category.
    It means this encoding does not take into account the relative importance of classification values.

  • As its observed, I decided to create custom mapping for values in case of considering importance of classification values.

In [ ]:
LE = LabelEncoder()
LE.fit(df['Education'])
mapping = dict(zip(LE.classes_, LE.transform(LE.classes_)))
mapping
Out[ ]:
{'Graduate': 0, 'Postgraduate': 1, 'Undergraduate': 2}
In [ ]:
edu_mapping = {'Graduate': 1, 'Postgraduate': 2, 'Undergraduate': 0}
liv_mapping = {'Alone': 0, 'Partner': 1}
df['Education'] = df['Education'].replace(edu_mapping)
df['Living_With'] = df['Living_With'].replace(liv_mapping)

4. Standardization¶

  • StandardScaler is subtract the mean of each feature from each observation and divides those values
    the std of the feature. It provides where the means of the features close around the 0 and 1 standard deviation.

  • The purpose of making this, PCA is sensitive the different ranges between the features. helps to equalize the scale of different numerical features in a dataset.

  • The other main purpose is that ,it helps to normalize the distribution of features that are not normally distributed.

In [ ]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(df_copy)
scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(scaler.transform(df_copy),columns= df_copy.columns )

before getting PCA, I wanted to loop general Kmeans model to see the silhouette score to make sure that
everything runs like expected

In [ ]:
n_clusters_range = range(2, 21)

silhouette_scores_kmeans = []
silhouette_scores_agg = []

for n_clusters in n_clusters_range:

    #KMeans Clustering
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, init='k-means++', n_init=1, random_state=42).fit(scaled_df)
    labels_kmeans = kmeans.labels_
    score_kmeans = silhouette_score(scaled_df, labels_kmeans)
    silhouette_scores_kmeans.append(score_kmeans)


plt.plot(n_clusters_range, silhouette_scores_kmeans, marker='o', label='KMeans')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette score')
plt.title('Silhouette scores for different values of n_clusters')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Silhouettte scores are low which is something acceptable. Important part here is that after PCA
I will use this silhouette scores as a metric compare both silhouette scores to see PCA was the right decision or not.

SCREE PLOT¶

  • Scree plot is a tool to procedure how many n_compnents for PCA.

  • It works the same prensib like Elbow method.

  • According to graphical inference, it is obvious to n_components = 3 is where the variance ratios are not decreasing.

  • After deciding PCA parameter as 3, I accepted to create 3-dimesional dataset.

In [ ]:

The elbow point strongly suggests that the appropriate number of components for PCA is 3

Elbow Method¶

  • The elbow method is a graphical technique for determining the optimal number of clusters within a clustering algorithm.

  • It is a widely employed strategy. It is not, however, a conclusive or infallible procedure, and its outcomes should be read with care.

  • According to below graph, the curviness of the graph is not that promising.

Profiling sonucunda ulasilan onemli tespitler burada belirtilmistir.

  • While (k)=2,

    • all the clusters are seperated between the TotalSpending and Income column correaltion.
    • It can be seen that the model only separates customers based on their income and spending, regardless of their education level, number of children, or shopping behavior related to campaigns.

  • While (k) = 3,

    • the model has taken into account other demographic characteristics and each cluster has its own unique identities.
    • For instance, in "Cluster 1", where intensity of spending values are between 1000 and 1500, none of the customers are parents.
    • Also the people who ara in the Cluster 2 as a mid level consumer are all parents.

  • While(k)=4,

    • Since the silhouette score is at its lowest, the distance between data points within clusters is very close.

    • In this scenario, the dataset is not inadequate in terms of observations, and the profiling is complex and messy.

    • It is very difficult to make a distinction about the clusters that are close to the bottom, especially in lower expenditures

summary¶

According to the research, n_clusters = 3 was determined, and 3 groups were formed.

Cluster 0:

  • Forms the lowest class of customers in the database.
  • This group responds least to campaigns compared to other clusters.

Cluster 1:

  • Forms the middle segment buyers in the customer database.
  • Their general education level is at least at the graduate level.
  • They are unmarried and have no children.
  • With slightly higher spending and income scales compared to the other two groups, they include the most valuable customers in our current customer base.
  • Their response rate to campaigns is higher than the other clusters.

Cluster 2:

  • Forms the lowest class of customers in the database.
  • The most distinguishing characteristic compared to Cluster 1 is that they generally have children and slightly lower spending and income levels.

Decided model
